This is the file that gets sent to the PDP-8
when the F6 function key is pressed.  It is
expected that PIP will be running and waiting
for text from the console when F6 is pressed.
A session will look something like this:

.R PIP

*TEXT.TX<TTY:

At this point F6 is pressed and the contents
of textfile are sent.  You will see the file
contents echoed here.  When all characters
have been sent an end of file character will
be sent which is a control-Z and will be
echoed as ^Z.  A new PIP prompt will appear
and you can type control-C to exit PIP.

^Z
*^C
.

And you are back in OS/8.  The file TEXT.TX
should be found on the DSK: device.

Note:  The TTY: handler only allows for 72
character lines and the 8 will not echo
the expected character when the 72nd char
is sent.  When the server sees the wrong
character echo it will issue an error
message, close out everything cleanly and
exit to the operating system.  You can
recover from this by restarting the server
with something like

./csd

The boot option should not be given as PIP
is still listening for the rest of the file.
You can get back to a PIP * prompt by sending
a control-Z.

This happens because the TTY: handler only
has room for a 72 character buffer and so
this is the longest line you can enter this
way.

I used this feature to get CONSYS.PA and
CONNON.PA onto the CSD1: platter so I could
compile them with real PAL8.


